    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Billionaires and Bakes Sales,'' by Timothy Egan (column, June 2), is not alone in noting the absence of debate on education topics in the 2008 campaign, despite the fact that voters consistently rank education as a top concern.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Billionaires and Bakes Sales,'' by Timothy Egan (column, June 2), is not alone in noting the absence of debate on education topics in the 2008 campaign, despite the fact that voters consistently rank education as a top concern.</p>
        <p>To fill that gap, the Education Writers Association, a nonprofit group representing education journalists around the country, is proposing one-on-one interviews with candidates and a panel of three education reporters.</p>
        <p>Those hourlong interviews would be available to everyone via Web stream and links to transcripts. The campaigns will receive invitations this week. We hope they take us up on our offer. (The Education Writers Association does not take positions on education issues and does not endorse or oppose candidates.)</p>
        <p>Richard Whitmire  Arlington, Va., June 4, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the Education Writers Association.</p>
      </block>
